      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial CFD solver with documented QA procedures and version control; solver release notes reviewed for relevant bug fixes.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R2 was used under a validated institutional license. QA documentation including solver verification test suite results and release notes for hemolysis-relevant modules was reviewed. Version control of case files maintained in institutional Git repository with tagged releases corresponding to each simulation campaign. Achieved level 2 exceeds the required level 1 for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmarked against canonical internal flow problems with known analytical solutions; order-of-accuracy confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Code verification performed using the method of manufactured solutions for the incompressible Navier-Stokes equations. Observed spatial order of accuracy of 1.97 (theoretical: 2.0) confirmed correct discretization implementation. Benchmark results archived and traceable to simulation campaign. Achieved level 2 exceeds required level 1."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence study with GCI < 5% on hemolysis QoI; at least three systematically refined meshes evaluated.",
      "rationale": "A mesh sensitivity study was performed using two mesh densities: a baseline mesh of 4.2 million cells and a refined mesh of 9.8 million cells. The Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the normalized index of hemolysis was computed as 11.3%, exceeding the 5% acceptance threshold. A third, further-refined mesh was not generated due to computational resource constraints during the project timeline. The team noted the elevated GCI but concluded that the conservative direction of mesh-induced error (over-prediction) was acceptable for the intended comparative use. Achieved level 1 does not meet the required level 2 for this factor."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental boundary conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid properties) documented and matched to CFD inputs within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "FDA GCBP experimental conditions are fully documented in the published dataset. Flow rates specified to ±0.05 L/min, rotational speed to ±10 RPM, and blood analog fluid properties (glycerol-water mixture) characterized at test temperature. CFD boundary conditions set to nominal experimental values; sensitivity to boundary condition uncertainty evaluated via ±2σ perturbation study showing <3% variation in NIH predictions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metrics (e.g., normalized error, validation uncertainty) computed for all QoIs; systematic bias characterized.",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison performed using normalized root-mean-square error (NRMSE) and validation uncertainty analysis per ASME V&V 20. NRMSE for NIH across five operating points: 14.2%. Validation uncertainty Uval = 19.8% (k=2). Experimental uncertainty Uexp = 8.4% (k=2). The model prediction falls within combined validation uncertainty bounds at four of five operating points. Systematic over-prediction bias of +6.1% identified and documented. Achieved level 3 exceeds required level 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, pressure head) are directly relevant to the COU decision quantity (relative hemolysis index RH).",
      "rationale": "The primary validation QoI — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) — is directly related to the COU decision quantity (relative hemolysis index RH) through a well-established linear scaling relationship. Secondary QoI (pressure head) validates hydraulic fidelity. Both QoIs are mechanistically linked to the hemolysis prediction pathway. Relevance confirmed by clinical subject matter expert review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities performed on geometry, operating conditions, and fluid properties sufficiently similar to the COU device and conditions.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump, which shares the same centrifugal impeller topology and operating envelope as the CPB device under assessment. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water) properties match within 4% of whole blood viscosity at relevant shear rates. Operating conditions span the clinical CPB flow range (3–6 L/min). Geometric similarity confirmed by overlay comparison; key clearance dimensions within 8% of COU device. Validation relevance assessed as adequate for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence confirmed; residuals reduced by at least 4 orders of magnitude; mass imbalance < 0.01%.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity and momentum equations, representing a reduction of greater than 5 orders of magnitude from initial residuals. Global mass imbalance confirmed below 0.005% for all operating points. Convergence monitored via area-averaged NIH monitor points; variation below 0.1% over final 500 iterations confirmed steady-state convergence."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation setup reviewed by independent analyst; boundary condition inputs and post-processing scripts verified against documented procedures.",
      "rationale": "Independent peer review of simulation setup performed by a second analyst not involved in case preparation. Boundary condition inputs verified against documented operating conditions. Post-processing scripts for NIH integration validated against manual calculation for one representative operating point. No use errors identified. Review documented in project technical record TR-2024-CPB-007."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence closure and hemolysis damage model selections justified by literature precedent and sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Steady RANS with k-ω SST turbulence closure selected based on established literature precedent for centrifugal blood pump CFD (Fraser et al., Hariharan et al.). Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis damage model applied with published coefficients. Model form sensitivity evaluated by comparison with Lagrangian particle tracking approach; NIH predictions within 12% across operating points. Model form uncertainty documented and propagated to validation uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs characterized with documented uncertainty; sensitivity of QoIs to input uncertainty evaluated.",
      "rationale": "Fluid properties (density, viscosity) characterized from manufacturer data sheets with ±2% uncertainty. Geometric inputs derived from engineering drawings with dimensional tolerances applied. One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis performed for five key inputs; NIH sensitivity to fluid viscosity (±2%) yields ±4.1% NIH variation, dominating the input uncertainty budget. Combined model input uncertainty estimated at ±5.8% (k=2)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; experimental dataset from published FDA study accepted as sufficient for comparative validation.",
      "rationale": "Test sample characterization not required at MRL 2 for this factor. The FDA GCBP experimental dataset is a publicly available, peer-reviewed reference dataset with documented sample preparation and measurement protocols. Sample-to-sample variability is reported in the original publication and incorporated into the experimental uncertainty estimate used in the validation comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
